the basis that you're using.

00:04:05.440 --> 00:04:11.590
Because for k and l
running in n by n.

00:04:11.590 --> 00:04:22.420
So this says that delta H
is diagonal in the chosen

00:04:22.420 --> 00:04:27.700
basis of the subspace vn.

00:04:27.700 --> 00:04:30.430
Delta H is not
diagonal elsewhere.

00:04:30.430 --> 00:04:34.210
On the big space, it
may not be diagonal.

00:04:34.210 --> 00:04:40.360
But on the little degenerate
space, it better be diagonal.

00:04:40.360 --> 00:04:44.470
So what it says is that, if you
want to start your perturbation

00:04:44.470 --> 00:04:48.790
theory, you cannot use an
arbitrary basis of states.

00:04:48.790 --> 00:04:50.530
Maybe you chose it wrong.

00:04:50.530 --> 00:04:54.830
You have to start in
the degenerate subspace

00:04:54.830 --> 00:04:59.910
with a basis that makes
the perturbation diagonal.

00:04:59.910 --> 00:05:03.360
And that's what our
little example had.

00:05:03.360 --> 00:05:07.100
It says, even to
begin with, you should

00:05:07.100 --> 00:05:11.520
have started with the basis
that makes the perturbation

00:05:11.520 --> 00:05:12.510
diagonal.

00:05:12.510 --> 00:05:16.830
In that case, you will find
the formulas giving you

00:05:16.830 --> 00:05:18.570
the right answers.

00:05:18.570 --> 00:05:26.090
And then, once you have
the matrix being diagonal,

00:05:26.090 --> 00:05:31.580
you can take l equal to k.

00:05:31.580 --> 00:05:33.860
And then you'll find
on the right hand

00:05:33.860 --> 00:05:40.400
sides Enk1 is equal to n.

00:05:40.400 --> 00:05:47.210
l is equal to k,
so n0k delta H n0k.

00:05:50.600 --> 00:05:55.400
So the energy corrections
are the diagonal elements

00:05:55.400 --> 00:05:56.450
